- Rollup Version: v1.18.0
- Operating System (or Browser): Linux 4.19.0-5-amd64
- Node Version: v10.15.2

### How Do We Reproduce?

```js
const local = {
	prop: false,
	meth (x) {
		this.prop = x;
	}
};

export const meth = (x) => {
	local.meth(x);
};

export const test = () => {
	if (local.prop === true) { // this is not constant
		console.log('true'); // this should remain
	}
};
```

### Expected Behaviour

The condition should remain since the value of `prop` can be modified from outside of the module.

### Actual Behaviour

The condition is removed.

### Notes

Some things that avoid this behaviour:

- Setting `prop` value using the object name `local` instead of `this`.
- Exporting the whole `local` object instead of wrapping the method.
- Using a variable in the module context for the condition.

Seems to depend on two things: determining object property mutability through more than one layer of function calls combined with the use of the `this` keyword and non-equivalence with any named references to the object.
